1
00:00:56,350 --> 00:00:59,710
Memorandum to Paramount Pictures,

2
00:00:59,710 --> 00:01:01,680
Hollywood, California,

3
00:01:01,710 --> 00:01:04,990
from Alexander Meyerheim.
Subject - my latest production.

4
00:01:04,990 --> 00:01:09,710
Gentlemen, while you sit back safely
in your air-conditioned offices

5
00:01:09,710 --> 00:01:14,510
we here... in the trenches
are progressing brilliantly.

6
00:01:14,510 --> 00:01:17,390
As to your anxieties
about the script, dismiss them.

7
00:01:17,390 --> 00:01:19,630
I talked to the author in Paris.

8
00:01:19,630 --> 00:01:24,110
He assures me that he has
at this moment 138 glorious pages

9
00:01:24,110 --> 00:01:29,250
which are even now being typed. I
plan to join him in Paris on Sunday.

10
00:01:29,310 --> 00:01:31,950
Period. Paragraph.

11
00:01:31,950 --> 00:01:35,870
Gentlemen, success is inevitable.

12
00:01:35,870 --> 00:01:38,350
An Alexander Meyerheim production

13
00:01:38,350 --> 00:01:41,230
of an original story and screenplay
by Richard Benson.

14
00:01:41,230 --> 00:01:43,950
- Richard Benson?
- You know him, my angel?

15
00:01:43,950 --> 00:01:45,748
Know him?

16
00:01:56,750 --> 00:01:59,834
I hate him! Richard Benson, phooey!

17
00:02:00,190 --> 00:02:03,630
It seems there are facets of him
you know even better than I do.

18
00:02:03,630 --> 00:02:06,190
I cannot imagine
when he finds time to write.

19
00:02:06,190 --> 00:02:09,630
Unfortunately, he had time
to write a script for me.

20
00:02:09,630 --> 00:02:11,000
The last ten pages were found

21
00:02:11,070 --> 00:02:14,240
floating off Malibu,
in a vodka bottle.

22
00:02:15,630 --> 00:02:18,390
Send the usual telegram to Benson.

23
00:02:18,390 --> 00:02:21,860
Richard assures me that for all
practical purposes he's on the wagon.

24
00:05:11,630 --> 00:05:13,342
It's open. Come in.

25
00:05:21,430 --> 00:05:24,590
- Yes?
- Mr Benson?

26
00:05:24,590 --> 00:05:26,988
You are the young lady
from the typing bureau?

27
00:05:27,030 --> 00:05:28,528
I am.

28
00:05:28,590 --> 00:05:30,817
If we are to have a happy
and harmonious relationship,

29
00:05:30,830 --> 00:05:33,470
I beg you, never answer
a question with a question.

30
00:05:33,470 --> 00:05:35,612
- Is that clear?
- Did I?

31
00:05:35,630 --> 00:05:38,270
There you go again, answering
a question with a question.

32
00:05:38,270 --> 00:05:40,910
My yes when you opened the door
was a question,

33
00:05:40,910 --> 00:05:42,622
question mark implied, of course.

34
00:05:42,670 --> 00:05:45,068
You know the difference
between implied and inferred?

35
00:05:45,070 --> 00:05:47,468
Isn't that a question?

36
00:05:48,350 --> 00:05:49,977
Yes.

37
00:05:50,030 --> 00:05:51,742
Then you answered my question
with a question.

38
00:05:51,790 --> 00:05:54,750
To imply is to indicate
without saying openly or directly,

39
00:05:54,750 --> 00:05:57,491
to infer is to conclude
from something known or assumed.

40
00:05:58,350 --> 00:06:02,376
- My name is Gabrielle Simpson.
- Is that a bird?

41
00:06:02,750 --> 00:06:06,948
I was told the job would take several
days. I had nobody to leave him with.

42
00:06:07,230 --> 00:06:09,200
Well, this is it. The office there,

43
00:06:09,230 --> 00:06:12,190
I live up here,
the terrace is out there.

44
00:06:12,190 --> 00:06:16,670
That grotesque object so prominent
on the horizon is the Eiffel Tower.

45
00:06:16,670 --> 00:06:19,630
I had it moved there to remind me
what town I'm in.

46
00:06:19,630 --> 00:06:23,470
If it offends you,
I'll have it taken away again.

47
00:06:23,470 --> 00:06:26,350
You live through here.
It's an adjoining room

48
00:06:26,350 --> 00:06:29,230
which no doubt to your mind
has terribly sinister connotations.

49
00:06:29,230 --> 00:06:30,772
- Not at all...
- If so dismiss them.

50
00:06:30,830 --> 00:06:33,470
I would have got you a room
down the hall

51
00:06:33,470 --> 00:06:36,910
but the joint's filled up.
Bastille Day weekend, all that.

52
00:06:36,910 --> 00:06:39,308
It's quite alright. I once worked
for an American novelist

53
00:06:39,310 --> 00:06:42,030
who only wrote in the bathtub.
I'm used to anything.

54
00:06:42,030 --> 00:06:44,910
You can unpack. In the bathtub?

55
00:06:44,910 --> 00:06:49,550
Yes. I gave him a packet of
bubble bath and we got on swimmingly.

56
00:06:49,550 --> 00:06:50,920
I see.

57
00:06:50,990 --> 00:06:54,270
Does that imply that
the bird's name is Richelieu?

58
00:06:54,270 --> 00:06:57,268
It's inferred, I believe,
rather than implied.

59
00:06:58,110 --> 00:07:00,851
Swimmingly.
Interesting figure of speech.

60
00:07:04,590 --> 00:07:08,016
You call the canary Richelieu
because you wanted a cardinal?

61
00:07:08,270 --> 00:07:10,068
That's very funny.

62
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:13,057
No, it isn't.
Just one of the hazards of being

63
00:07:13,070 --> 00:07:16,670
a famous international wit,
which I am. Have to keep trying.

64
00:07:16,670 --> 00:07:19,790
I can't tell you how delighted I am
by this assignment, Mr Benson.

65
00:07:19,790 --> 00:07:22,910
And to have the opportunity to work
with a screenwriter of your stature.

66
00:07:22,910 --> 00:07:26,190
I'm interested in cinema myself.
I'm sure I can learn a great deal.

67
00:07:26,190 --> 00:07:27,303
Thank you.

68
00:07:27,390 --> 00:07:31,230
Last month I worked for Roger Roussin
the New Wave director. You know him?

69
00:07:31,230 --> 00:07:33,200
I'm more of an Old Wave man.

70
00:07:33,230 --> 00:07:36,110
The picture's terribly interesting.
Very avant-garde.

71
00:07:36,110 --> 00:07:40,110
About people who go to this party
and decide not to play Scrabble.

72
00:07:40,110 --> 00:07:43,365
<i>It was called The Scrabble Game
Will Not Take Place.</i>

73
00:07:44,110 --> 00:07:46,422
His next one's about a girl
who won't have a birthday party -

74
00:07:46,430 --> 00:07:48,486
<i>Blow Out No Candles.</i>

75
00:07:48,510 --> 00:07:51,710
Roger believes what's important
on screen is what doesn't happen.

76
00:07:51,710 --> 00:07:54,108
Does your film have a title yet?

77
00:07:54,110 --> 00:07:55,480
Of course.

78
00:07:57,070 --> 00:07:59,950
<i>The Girl Who Stole
the Eiffel Tower.</i>

79
00:07:59,950 --> 00:08:03,790
<i>The Girl Who Stole the Eiffel
Tower. It sounds fascinating.</i>

80
00:08:03,790 --> 00:08:04,988
The title is symbolic?

81
00:08:05,070 --> 00:08:08,154
She doesn't really steal
the Eiffel Tower. Does she?

82
00:08:10,270 --> 00:08:12,326
What's the story about?

83
00:08:12,350 --> 00:08:15,310
It's an action-suspense, erm, ...

84
00:08:15,310 --> 00:08:18,030
..romantic melodrama.
With lots of comedy, of course.

85
00:08:18,030 --> 00:08:22,350
And deep down underneath
a substrata of social comment.

86
00:08:22,350 --> 00:08:24,577
Oh. Well, if I could see
the pages you've written

87
00:08:24,590 --> 00:08:27,845
I could estimate
the size of the typing job.

88
00:08:28,670 --> 00:08:31,411
The pages, my dear girl,
are right here.

89
00:08:32,910 --> 00:08:36,030
An Alexander Meyerheim production.

90
00:08:36,030 --> 00:08:38,590
<i>The Girl Who Stole
the Eiffel Tower.</i>

91
00:08:38,590 --> 00:08:42,110
Original story and screenplay by
Richard Benson.

92
00:08:42,110 --> 00:08:44,830
Here, with a page or two
of interestingly photographed

93
00:08:44,830 --> 00:08:47,470
establishing shots,
possibly from a helicopter,

94
00:08:47,470 --> 00:08:50,830
- a boy and a girl meet.
- But Mr Benson...

95
00:08:50,830 --> 00:08:53,870
Now, after some chitchat,

96
00:08:53,870 --> 00:08:57,070
getting-to-know-you stuff,
which I do so brilliantly,

97
00:08:57,070 --> 00:09:00,510
we feel an unconscious attraction
between the two.

98
00:09:00,510 --> 00:09:04,590
An indication to the audience
of the tremulous beginnings of love.

99
00:09:04,590 --> 00:09:06,817
And then, conflict!

100
00:09:06,830 --> 00:09:10,590
We can tell by the music
how deeply fraught with danger

101
00:09:10,590 --> 00:09:12,732
the whole situation is.

102
00:09:12,750 --> 00:09:16,670
And now, ... our first switch.

103
00:09:16,670 --> 00:09:20,350
The audience gasps when they realise
they've been fooled.

104
00:09:20,350 --> 00:09:23,950
Things are not what they seem.
Not at all.

105
00:09:23,950 --> 00:09:28,270
In fact, the whole situation
is completely reversed,

106
00:09:28,270 --> 00:09:32,110
involving
the magnificently ingenious

107
00:09:32,110 --> 00:09:35,708
switch... on the switch.

108
00:09:37,710 --> 00:09:40,830
Amazed by the sudden turn of events,

109
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:45,713
the boy and girl realise how gravely
they've misjudged each other.

110
00:09:48,830 --> 00:09:50,457
At that moment,

111
00:09:50,510 --> 00:09:53,670
the music turns ominous once more.

112
00:09:53,670 --> 00:09:58,670
They become aware of the danger
that they're in and the chase is on!

113
00:09:58,670 --> 00:10:00,382
Spinning tyres, rooftops,

114
00:10:00,430 --> 00:10:04,430
long shots of tiny figures racing
through the fear-gripped city.

115
00:10:04,430 --> 00:10:08,830
When suddenly in a deserted alley
we see, seated on a garbage can,

116
00:10:08,830 --> 00:10:11,057
licking its wet rain-bedraggled fur,

117
00:10:11,070 --> 00:10:13,212
close shot, the cat!

118
00:10:14,110 --> 00:10:17,870
Now, as we build
step by step to the climax,

119
00:10:17,870 --> 00:10:19,497
the music soars.

120
00:10:19,550 --> 00:10:21,862
And there, totally oblivious

121
00:10:21,870 --> 00:10:25,070
of the torrential rain
pouring down upon them,

122
00:10:25,070 --> 00:10:29,230
the two fall happily and tenderly
into each other's arms.

123
00:10:29,230 --> 00:10:33,710
And as the audience drools
with sublimated sexual pleasure,

124
00:10:33,710 --> 00:10:37,550
the two enormous and highly paid
heads come together

125
00:10:37,550 --> 00:10:40,390
for that ultimate
and inevitable moment.

126
00:10:40,390 --> 00:10:43,710
The final, earth-moving,

127
00:10:43,710 --> 00:10:46,910
studio-rent-paying, theatre-filling,

128
00:10:46,910 --> 00:10:48,708
popcorn-selling...

129
00:10:51,630 --> 00:10:53,514
..kiss.

130
00:10:53,550 --> 00:10:56,291
Fade out. The end.

131
00:10:58,910 --> 00:11:03,622
That's it. 138 pages. Why make it
longer? We'd only have to cut later.

132
00:11:03,870 --> 00:11:06,012
- Mr Benson...
- Yes?

133
00:11:07,710 --> 00:11:11,908
This screenplay,
when does it have to be finished?

134
00:11:13,230 --> 00:11:15,286
Well, let's see, today is Friday.

135
00:11:15,310 --> 00:11:19,070
My friend and in this case patron
and producer Mr Alexander Meyerheim

136
00:11:19,070 --> 00:11:22,582
arrives in Paris from Cannes
at ten o'clock on...

137
00:11:23,710 --> 00:11:28,430
..Sunday morning.
Which happens to be Bastille Day.

138
00:11:28,430 --> 00:11:31,470
Perfect! 10:01 we hand him
the completed script

139
00:11:31,470 --> 00:11:35,710
and then you and I celebrate. Drink
champagne, dance in the streets,

140
00:11:35,710 --> 00:11:37,852
whatever they do on July 14th.

141
00:11:37,870 --> 00:11:42,925
You're very kind but I have a date.
You haven't written anything at all?

142
00:11:44,510 --> 00:11:45,794
You have a date?

143
00:11:46,350 --> 00:11:50,119
You mean this entire movie
has to be done in two days?

144
00:11:51,150 --> 00:11:56,190
Miss Simpson, if you aren't up to
your part of the job, tell me now.

145
00:11:56,190 --> 00:11:59,310
- I can find someone else.
- No, I didn't mean that.

146
00:11:59,310 --> 00:12:02,990
It's just that it's,
well, rather unusual, isn't it?

147
00:12:02,990 --> 00:12:04,446
Not for me.

148
00:12:04,590 --> 00:12:07,230
I imagine you've given it
a great deal of thought?

149
00:12:07,230 --> 00:12:08,857
No, I haven't.

150
00:12:10,670 --> 00:12:12,468
So what have you been doing?

151
00:12:14,590 --> 00:12:18,510
What any red-blooded
American screenwriter

152
00:12:18,510 --> 00:12:20,566
would or should have been doing

153
00:12:20,590 --> 00:12:23,950
for the first 19 and a fraction weeks
of his employment.

154
00:12:23,950 --> 00:12:25,748
Water-skiing in St Tropez,

155
00:12:25,790 --> 00:12:28,788
lying in the sun in Antibes,
studying Greek.

156
00:12:29,230 --> 00:12:30,428
Greek?

157
00:12:30,510 --> 00:12:33,390
There was this starlet
representing the Greek film industry

158
00:12:33,390 --> 00:12:35,870
at the Cannes festival.

159
00:12:35,870 --> 00:12:38,350
Then of course
a few weeks unlearning Greek,

160
00:12:38,350 --> 00:12:40,910
which involved
a considerable amount of vodka

161
00:12:40,910 --> 00:12:43,308
and an unpremeditated trip to Madrid
for the bullfights,

162
00:12:43,310 --> 00:12:46,670
which fortunately, since
I can't bear the sight of blood,

163
00:12:46,670 --> 00:12:48,726
had long since gone on to Seville.

164
00:12:48,750 --> 00:12:52,430
Weeks 17 and 18 were spent
in the casino at Monte Carlo,

165
00:12:52,430 --> 00:12:55,630
in a somewhat ill-advised attempt
to win enough money

166
00:12:55,630 --> 00:12:59,310
to buy back my $5,000-a-week,
plus expenses, contract

167
00:12:59,310 --> 00:13:02,990
from my friend, employer and patron,
Mr Alexander Meyerheim,

168
00:13:02,990 --> 00:13:06,510
thus not having to write the picture
at all. Take a note.

169
00:13:06,510 --> 00:13:09,710
For the textbook I will someday do
on the art of screenwriting,

170
00:13:09,710 --> 00:13:14,030
never play 13, 31
and the corners thereof

171
00:13:14,030 --> 00:13:18,142
for any serious length of time for
any serious money. It doesn't work.

172
00:13:18,910 --> 00:13:21,480
And now I have to. Shall we begin?

173
00:13:24,030 --> 00:13:26,590
An Alexander Meyerheim production.

174
00:13:26,590 --> 00:13:30,531
<i>Caps, quotes. The Girl Who Stole
the Eiffel Tower.</i>

175
00:13:31,310 --> 00:13:32,594
You do like the title?

176
00:13:32,670 --> 00:13:35,870
Oh, yes,
it certainly sounds intriguing.

177
00:13:35,870 --> 00:13:39,725
It intrigued Meyerheim, too.
He bought the title, script unseen.

178
00:13:40,590 --> 00:13:44,190
Original story and screenplay
by Richard Benson.

179
00:13:44,190 --> 00:13:47,790
Page one. Fade in. Exterior.
Paris, naturally.

180
00:13:47,790 --> 00:13:49,588
Let's see, night or day?

181
00:13:51,470 --> 00:13:52,583
Day.

182
00:13:53,550 --> 00:13:57,662
Begin... with a shot of...
of the Eiffel Tower.

183
00:13:58,350 --> 00:14:02,190
<i>The camera zooms in. Standing
windswept and alone on a platform</i>

184
00:14:02,190 --> 00:14:05,788
<i>is a mysterious woman in black.
She glances at her watch.</i>

185
00:14:06,350 --> 00:14:08,320
And we see...

186
00:14:14,030 --> 00:14:16,830
How the hell do I know?
Mysterious woman in black.

187
00:14:16,830 --> 00:14:19,228
Oh, how the mighty have fallen!

188
00:14:19,230 --> 00:14:23,950
Mustn't be obvious. Don't give the
whole story too early. OK. Fade in.

189
00:14:23,950 --> 00:14:28,062
Exterior, le Sacre Coeur. Day.

190
00:14:29,390 --> 00:14:30,418
No...

191
00:14:31,550 --> 00:14:33,177
Make that, erm, ...

192
00:14:34,190 --> 00:14:36,332
..the Grand Palais.

193
00:14:39,070 --> 00:14:40,440
Uh-uh.

194
00:14:41,390 --> 00:14:43,702
We've got to give the audience

195
00:14:43,710 --> 00:14:47,651
the taste and smell
of the real Paris.

196
00:14:50,110 --> 00:14:51,223
OK.

197
00:14:52,590 --> 00:14:55,950
<i>Exterior. Christian Dior.
The camera pans</i>

198
00:14:55,950 --> 00:15:00,270
<i>"and now we see a white Rolls"-"Royce"
pull up and come to a stop.</i>

199
00:15:00,270 --> 00:15:04,110
<i>No, wait a minute,
make that a white Bentley.</i>

200
00:15:04,110 --> 00:15:05,908
<i>It's chicer.</i>

201
00:15:05,950 --> 00:15:09,550
<i>A chauffeur in white livery
leaps out and opens the door.</i>

202
00:15:09,550 --> 00:15:13,390
<i>From inside emerges
some classically glamorous star</i>

203
00:15:13,390 --> 00:15:16,131
<i>like, erm, Marlene Dietrich.</i>

204
00:15:17,310 --> 00:15:20,830
<i>And now she... Erm...</i>

205
00:15:20,830 --> 00:15:22,114
<i>Dot, dot, dot.</i>

206
00:15:23,310 --> 00:15:26,308
<i>She sweeps majestically
into the store and...</i>

207
00:15:28,030 --> 00:15:32,270
That's all we see of her. Makes no
sense but Alex would have loved it.

208
00:15:32,270 --> 00:15:36,639
He could have stolen the Bentley and
afte"rw"ards charged it to the picture.

209
00:15:38,670 --> 00:15:41,390
- What d'you say your name was?
- Gabrielle Simpson.

210
00:15:41,390 --> 00:15:44,302
- How long have you lived in Paris?
- Two years.

211
00:15:45,070 --> 00:15:46,868
And you came here to write.

212
00:15:47,230 --> 00:15:49,710
Well, that, too, but mostly to...

213
00:15:49,710 --> 00:15:52,590
I don't know how to say it exactly.
Live.

214
00:15:52,590 --> 00:15:54,217
Live?

215
00:15:54,270 --> 00:15:55,812
Would you mind...?

216
00:16:00,670 --> 00:16:03,230
You were saying
you came here to live.

217
00:16:03,230 --> 00:16:07,942
Yes. For the first six months I made
a comprehensive study of depravity.

218
00:16:09,150 --> 00:16:10,263
No kidding?

219
00:16:10,350 --> 00:16:12,920
Seriously. Never got to bed
before eight in the morning.

220
00:16:14,430 --> 00:16:18,110
Who knows how many cups of
poisonous black coffee I consumed?

221
00:16:18,110 --> 00:16:21,870
I didn't drink then, so it was hard
to get totally into the spirit.

222
00:16:21,870 --> 00:16:25,550
Depravity can be terribly boring
if you don't smoke or drink.

223
00:16:25,550 --> 00:16:27,948
But a person must try to grow.

224
00:16:27,950 --> 00:16:32,270
And the guy you're dating on Bastille
Day, is he part of the process?

225
00:16:32,270 --> 00:16:35,310
No, he's just a friend.
A struggling young actor.

226
00:16:35,310 --> 00:16:37,708
An actor?!

227
00:16:37,710 --> 00:16:39,080
Ewww...

228
00:16:39,150 --> 00:16:42,510
A tragic relationship to begin with.

229
00:16:42,510 --> 00:16:47,310
I hope he's not a method actor, who
scratches and mumbles and pauses,

230
00:16:47,310 --> 00:16:51,150
thereby destroying the impeccable
rhythm of the author's prose.

231
00:16:51,150 --> 00:16:54,405
No, he's a little intense
but lots of fun.

232
00:16:55,150 --> 00:16:57,292
Uh-huh? Yeah, well...

233
00:16:58,110 --> 00:17:03,150
And you and this... actor, what
do you plan to do on Bastille Day?

234
00:17:03,150 --> 00:17:07,630
We'll spend the whole day together.
First, breakfast at a little caf,

235
00:17:07,630 --> 00:17:10,270
then we'll dance
from one end of Paris to the other,

236
00:17:10,270 --> 00:17:14,270
opera at five, then the guards
and the singing of The Marseillaise,

237
00:17:14,270 --> 00:17:15,726
off to Montmartre for the fireworks,

238
00:17:15,790 --> 00:17:19,230
then supper and champagne
and, you know, live.

239
00:17:19,230 --> 00:17:22,750
- You really like it, don't you?
- What?

240
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:24,548
Life.

241
00:17:24,590 --> 00:17:27,160
Every morning when I wake up
